title = "Tumbling and Vibratory Mass Finishing"

content = """
Mass finishing processes — tumbling and vibratory finishing — are used at Ridgecrest Metalworks to deburr, edge-break, clean, and surface-finish large batches of smaller metal components economically and consistently. Both methods process parts in bulk without individual fixturing.

Barrel tumbling (rotary tumbling) loads parts, abrasive media, compound, and water into a rotating hexagonal or octagonal barrel. As the barrel rotates, the media and parts cascade over one another, abrading sharp edges, removing burrs, and smoothing surfaces. Cycle times range from 30 minutes to several hours depending on material hardness and required finish. This method produces aggressive cutting action and is suited to heavy deburring of castings, forgings, and stamped parts. A drawback is part-on-part impingement damage for fragile or precision components, which must be evaluated before using this method.

Vibratory finishing uses a bowl or trough vibrated at controlled frequency and amplitude. Parts and media move in a toroidal helical flow pattern, providing uniform contact without the aggressive tumbling action. Vibratory finishing is preferred for precision components, thin-walled parts, and parts requiring dimensional control since the process is gentler than barrel tumbling. Bowl vibratory machines are suited to batch processing; trough (linear) vibratory machines accommodate continuous flow for high-volume production.

Media selection drives the finish achieved:
- Ceramic media (triangles, cylinders, stars): Standard deburring and surface conditioning on steel and aluminum
- Plastic media: Gentler cutting; used for aluminum, brass, and soft metals to reduce dimensional stock removal
- Stainless steel pins or balls: Burnishing (bright polishing) without cutting; produces a compacted, lustrous surface
- Walnut shell or corn cob: Dry polishing and final cleaning after wet processes

Compounds (liquid chemistry added to the water) serve as lubricants, brighteners, or rust inhibitors and affect both the cut rate and the final appearance. Process parameters — media-to-part ratio, water level, compound concentration, cycle time, and frequency — are documented on process sheets and must be followed consistently to achieve repeatable results.

After finishing, parts are separated from media using a separator screen, rinsed, and dried promptly to prevent flash rusting on steel parts. Parts are inspected for residual burrs, surface finish level, and any processing damage before release to the next operation.
"""

